3. The distance traversed by Mr. Baumgartner before he reached maximum velocity was approximately:

496.Solution:
3. The correct answer is $\mathrm{D}$. The initial velocity $\left(v_{i}\right)$ of Felix Baumgartner in the vertical direction is 0 , his final velocity $\left(v_{f}\right)$ is $373 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$, and the acceleration due to gravity is $9.8 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}^{2}$ (although in reality it is probably slightly lower because of the significantly MCAT

large jumping altitude). The equation of motion that can be used to determine the distance traversed by Baumgartner is:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { displacement } & =\frac{(\text { final velocity })^{2}-(\text { initial velocity })^{2}}{2 \times(\text { acceleration due to gravity) }} \\
& =\frac{\left(373 \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{s}}\right)^{2}-\left(0 \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{s}}\right)^{2}}{19.6 \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{s}^{2}}} \\
& =\frac{139,129 \frac{\mathrm{m}^{2}}{\mathrm{~s}^{2}}-0}{19.6 \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{s}^{2}}} \\
& =7098 \mathrm{~m}
\end{aligned}
$$

