4. The drag force, $F$ drag, can be expressed in terms of the terminal velocity, $v t$, as $F$ drag $=C v_{t}^{2}$, where $C$ is a drag constant. The value of the drag constant for Mr. Baumgartner is:

497.Solution:
4. The correct answer is $\mathbf{A}$. When an object in free fall reaches terminal velocity, it is in equilibrium. In other words, the drag force acting upward becomes equal in magnitude yet opposite in direction to the object's weight, or:

$$
\begin{aligned}
F_{d} & =F_{g} \\
C v_{t}^{2} & =\mathrm{mg} \\
C & =\frac{\mathrm{mg}}{v_{t}^{2}}=\frac{1,156 \mathrm{~N}}{\left(373 \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{s}}\right)^{2}}=\frac{1,156 \mathrm{~N}}{139,129 \frac{\mathrm{m}^{2}}{\mathrm{~s}^{2}}}=0.008 \frac{\mathrm{kg}}{\mathrm{m}}
\end{aligned}
$$
